[{"id":"VR877766","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">Show all your work for each part of the question. The parts within the question may not have equal weight.</p><br/><div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Figure 1 shows a diagram of the refraction of incident light through air, oil, and water. From top to bottom, air, oil, and water are shown as three separate sections, separated by two horizontal lines. Incident light is indicated at the top of the diagram, in air, and extends vertically downward through the air. A dashed vertical line is drawn through the oil. A wave curve reaches a peak to the left of the dashed vertical line, about halfway through the oil, and has two troughs, each to the right of the dashed vertical line. One is at the boundary of the air and oil, and one is at the boundary of the oil and water. A downward pointing arrow is shown in oil, indicating downward movement.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR877766.g03.svg\"/></div>\n<p class=\"passage_para\">A thin layer of oil floats on water, as shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span>. Light of wavelength <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda\"><math alttext=\"lambda\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>λ</mi></math></span></span> in air is incident normally upon the air-oil interface. For the case where the oil thickness is equal to one wavelength in the oil, the transmitted wave in the oil is represented at a specific instant in time.</p>\n<p class=\"passage_para\">The indexes of refraction of air, the oil, and water are <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n sub A\"><math alttext=\"n sub A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mtext>A</mtext></msub></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n sub O\"><math alttext=\"n sub O\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mtext>O</mtext></msub></math></span></span>, and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n sub W\"><math alttext=\"n sub W\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mtext>W</mtext></msub></math></span></span>, respectively, where <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n sub O is greater than n sub W, which is greater than, open parenthesis, N sub A equals 1.00, close parenthesis\"><math alttext=\"n sub O is greater than n sub W, which is greater than, open parenthesis, N sub A equals 1.00, close parenthesis\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mtext>O</mtext></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi>n</mi><mtext>W</mtext></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><mrow><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>n</mi><mtext>A</mtext></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mtext>.</mtext><mn>00</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow></math></span></span>.</p>\n</div></div></div></div><div class=\"item_part part_id:A part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"A\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a) In figures <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span>, and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"4\"><math alttext=\"4\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>4</mn></math></span></span>, <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">sketch</span> representations of the waves listed below for the same instant of time shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span>. For reference, the wave representation from Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> is indicated by a dashed-line curve in each figure, and a vertical scale is indicated as well. Your sketches should indicate the relative wavelengths and the phases of the waves. You do NOT need to indicate the relative amplitudes of the waves.</p><ul class=\"unordered_list style:1\"><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\">Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>: The incident light wave in air.</p></li><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\">Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span>: The light wave in air reflected from the air-oil interface.</p></li><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\">Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"4\"><math alttext=\"4\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>4</mn></math></span></span>: The light wave in the oil reflected from the oil-water interface.</p></li></ul><p class=\"stem_paragraph\"><span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">Notes:</span> For the waves in air, the waves should start at the air-oil interface and extend for at least two wavelengths. For the wave in the oil, the wave should extend for the entire thickness of the oil layer.</p><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Figures 2, 3, and 4 each show a diagram. From top to bottom in each diagram, air, oil, and water are shown as three separate sections, separated by two horizontal lines. There are 14 dashed horizontal lines in the air section, 3 dashed horizontal lines in the oil section, and no lines in the water section. A dashed vertical line is drawn through the three sections. In the oil section of each diagram, a dashed wave curve reaches a peak to the left of the dashed vertical line, about halfway through the oil, and has two troughs, each to the right of the dashed vertical line. One is at the boundary of the air and oil, and one is at the boundary of the oil and water.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR877766.g04.svg\"/></div></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR877766_rubric"},{"id":"VR877766","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:B part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"B\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The wave that is reflected from the oil-water interface and then transmitted through the oil-air interface can interfere with the wave that is reflected from the air-oil interface.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b) <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Derive</span> an expression for the minimum thickness <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t sub min \"><math alttext=\"t sub min \" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>t</mi><mi>min</mi></msub></math></span></span> of the layer of oil that will result in maximum destructive interference of the two reflected waves in air. Express your answer in terms of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n sub A\"><math alttext=\"n sub A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mtext>A</mtext></msub></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n sub O\"><math alttext=\"n sub O\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mtext>O</mtext></msub></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n sub W\"><math alttext=\"n sub W\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mtext>W</mtext></msub></math></span></span>, the wavelength <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda\"><math alttext=\"lambda\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>λ</mi></math></span></span> of the light in air, and physical constants, as appropriate.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR877766_rubric"},{"id":"VR877766","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:C part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"C\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Consider liquids with different refractive indexes <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n sub L\"><math alttext=\"n sub L\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mtext>L</mtext></msub></math></span></span> that could produce a thin film floating on the surface of water, where <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n sub L\"><math alttext=\"n sub L\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mtext>L</mtext></msub></math></span></span> could be now be either greater than or less than <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n sub W\"><math alttext=\"n sub W\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mtext>W</mtext></msub></math></span></span> − but still greater than <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n sub A equals 1.00\"><math alttext=\"n sub A equals 1.00\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mtext>A</mtext></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mtext>.</mtext><mn>00</mn></math></span></span>.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(c) On the axes in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"5\"><math alttext=\"5\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>5</mn></math></span></span>, <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">sketch</span> a graph of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t sub min\"><math alttext=\"t sub min\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>t</mi><mi>min</mi></msub></math></span></span>, the minimum liquid film thickness that results in destructive interference for reflected waves of fixed wavelength <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda\"><math alttext=\"lambda\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>λ</mi></math></span></span> in air.</p><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Figure 5 shows the first quadrant of a coordinate plane. The horizontal axis is labeled n sub L. The value 1 is indicated at the origin and the value n sub W is indicated halfway along the axis. A dashed vertical grid line extends upward from n sub W. The vertical axis is labeled t sub min and the value 0 is indicated at the origin.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR877766.g06.svg\"/></div></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR877766_rubric"},{"id":"VR877766","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:D part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"D\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Consider a second scenario where air is replaced by a thick layer of a liquid that can float on top of the oil, and where the new liquid has an index of refraction greater than that of both the oil and water. Assume that the light wave in the oil has the same wavelength and phase as shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span>.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(d) For the diagrams you drew in part (a), <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">indicate</span> one feature that would be different for the second scenario. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Justify</span> your answer.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR877766_rubric"}]